BKMR model for birth weight

Sheena Martenies

2/24/2020

This document summarizes the prelimiary results of the Bayesian Kernel Machine Regression (BKMR) model for birth weight. The analysis builds on the original CEI paper, where we developed an index to characterize combined exposures to environmental and social determinants of health and their associations with birth weight and adiposity at birth in the Healthy Start cohort.

Here I am presenting the results of the preliminary BKMR model for birth weight.

For this analysis, we take a subset of those predictors (as selected using the NPS algorithm) and fit a BKMR model to assess independent and joint effects of the exposures. When implementing the NPB model, We used a (conservative) PIP of 0.25 determine which exposures would carry over to the BKMR model. The NPB model selected 9 of the original 19 exposures: mean PM2.5, percent impervious surfaces, distance to mines or oil and gas wells, cardiovascular hospitalization rates, respiratory hospitalization rates, property crime rates, the percentage of the population with less than a high school diploma, the percentage of the civilian workforce population that was unemployed, and the percentage of households living in poverty.

Prior to fitting the BKMR model, the outcome, exposure, and individual-level covariates (based on the literature and the previous CEI paper) were scaled.

Of the original 1410 mother-child pairs in the cohort, we have complete data for 780 (55%) pairs.

Results summary

The results so far suggest:

  • the overall mixture has an inverse relationship with birth weight, where higher exposures are associated with lower birth weight
  • the three exposures with the highest PIPs are respiratory hospitalization rates (PIP = 0.41), percentage of households in poverty (PIP = 0.38), and percent impervious surface (POP = 0.35)
  • Some of the exposures displayed (potenitally) non-linear exposure-response curves (including PM2.5 and property crime rates) though these were not the most important exposures
  • The effects of individual exposures were influenced by the other exposures (evidence of effect modification?)
  • The stongest relationship with birth weight was observed for respiratory hospitalization rates
  • There was little evidence of interations?
